Native Americans realized the value of fire for the prairie and were responsible for many of the fires that occurred over the past several millennia in this area.

#RxFire https://t.co/trBCsbA7LP

In fact, prairies need fire to help them thrive against the competition from woody vegetation that will take over through succession if there are no fires. 

#RxFire https://t.co/eAWu98SXxa

Prairies respond very positively to fire and native plants are rejuvenated because the burning of dead vegetation releases nutrients for the plants to use and allows the soil temperatures to warm up more quickly in the spring.

#RxFire https://t.co/M6qbK06j4O

North American prairies evolved with fire as a common occurrence in their ecosystem. 

 #RxFire https://t.co/saAN2zODxO

I worked in refugee resettlement for over a decade. 

From a purely clinical POV, it's fascinating watching the public discourse re: refugees fleeing Ukraine and how it differs from other refugee situations worldwide -- both past and present. 

If you know, you know.

@athada Internally Displaced Persons (IDPs) have far less protections via international conventions than do refugees as well. Countries are required to house refugees in a way they are not for IDPs. Another wrinkle.

@athada Another piece of the puzzle is this is a war of aggression, of one country invading another, in the case of Ukraine and Russia. 

Both Syrian and Yemen are experiencing internally displaced populations, more a civil war situation. I wonder how much impact that has as well.
@athada This is me wearing my "refugee resettlement professional" hat for a second here. No judgement on your post. Simply observing and wondering.

@athada It's fascinating to watch people identify so much more w/Ukraine and refugees fleeing the conflict w/Russian than w/Syrian or Yemenese families facing the same types of conflict and impossible choices. 

I imagine it's our shared European heritage and culture.

Our meeting today ended w/fact that we're seeing a rise in local cases of COVID-19 again. We don't know what to expect or how we will need to respond to fight hunger. Will need increase again, as they have with other COVID surges? No idea.

But, we are prepared. In partnership.

If anyone tells you they know what they are doing or what the future holds, they are lying through their teeth. 

We are making this up as we go. Thanks to COVID-19, the partnerships between my rural community's food pantries is solid as a rock.

How do we balance that desire for anonymity and privacy during food insecurity trauma that's prized w/the mobile food distribution model with the value of the deep relationships that are built when a guest used to come into a food pantry to shop for their food? 

I don't know.

Similary, mobile food distributions have been a life-line to rural communities during COVID-19. For many households facing food insecurity for the first time in their lives, the drive-up model and the anonymity it afforded, was appreciated and valued.

We are seeing a huge cultural shift happening. We all became used to ordering our groceries online. I expect most rural food pantries to permanently move to a curbside pick-up model of pre-packaged food boxes, even after COVID safety precuations no longer make it necessary.

A MAJOR shift we are seeing is that food pantry guests no longer want to 'shop' indoors for their food. A recent survey only had one respondant say they wanted to go back to coming inside the food pantries to select their food and receive their food boxes.

In the early days of the pandemic, all our area food pantries shut down their then-normal food pantry shopping. Everything moved to curbside pick-up for the health and safety of food pantry staff, volunteers, and the guests who needed the food due to COVID-19 related job losses.

We share freezer space between our rural food pantries, pick up food orders when another pantry isn't able to, share our own developing best practices to each other. The landscape is constantly shifting beneath our feet right now, and we are determined to lift each other up.

It's insane what we have accomplished to fight skyrocketing hunger rates in Marshall County. The partnerships that have been formed by food pantries that dot our rural area are as solid as a rock. We have been through hell together the past year and have a created a solid team.

Which brings me to this. If you, dear reader, or someone whom you love is experiencing neurological symptoms that seemingly have NO explantion, please do not hesitate to reach out to me.

So, here's the thing. Talking to her, I realized just HOW MUCH I've learned. Lines of exploration, caring neurologists to call, questions to ask and answers to prioritize and seek out. Speaking with her, I discovered I've learned much about searching for the unsearchable.

I shared EVERY SINGLE TIP and trick I could think of, spur of the moment, standing in that parking lot. Anything and everything to help her navigate an incredibly lonely, complicated, and scarily expensive road.
I told her how valuable genetic counselors are when searching for those long-awaited answers (with the help of my incredible cousin).

She and her husband are living what Dustin and I lived through, only a few short years ago.

I understood. 

I shared the genealogical investigating I did (with the help of my amazing mother-in-law).

They, too, are having specialists slam doors in their faces, being told nothing is wrong -- all while facing that terrible, chronic, debilitating pain that -- no matter how hard someone tries -- no one truly understands until they have experienced it themselves.

Scary symptoms. Symptoms that only continued to get worse as time went on. 

She understood. 

Turns out her husband is experiencing unexplained neurological symptoms too.

... telling us we were simply 'confused' and surely the symptoms we were describing were only figments of our imagination. Endless rounds of tests finding nothing 'wrong' with Dustin that could explain his debilitating and chronic pain, his other symptoms.

Over the next few minutes she asked me how we eventually discovered Dustin's exceedingly rare diagnosis. I shared that it took us over 3 years of constant searching, various neurologists and specialists telling us we were making up his symptoms or 'looking for his next high.'

During the course of my day today I had a long conversation with a woman. She saw Dustin's wheelchair and asked me if he had MS. I told her he does not, that he has HSP - hereditary spastic paraplegia.

How do we get people to change behaviors in this moment? When we see our medical systems failing around us? I just don't know. But we have to continue to try. Try anything and everything.

I don't have answers. Just questions and fear. Stay safe, friends. We are in this together.

Instead of a quick-hitting disaster like a flood -- get people to safety, triage medical care, get aid out, long-term recovery -- COVID-19 is a slow-moving giant. 

We are at our weakest now after more than a 1/2 year of pandemic life when the pandemic is at its most dangerous.

We are asking people to not see family and friends during the holidays. A Thanksgiving and Christmas this year that we are all stumbling into, weary, desperate to see family again. To connect. TO FEEL NORMAL. 

When people are scared, they want to feel safe. Normalcy feels safe.

NONE of us has ever lived through a pandemic in living memory. We are asking people to completely re-write all social and business interactions to stop the spread. The health outcomes if not are clear. 

But in times of crisis, people want the FAMILIAR. They cling to it.

COVID-19 is completely different. We have shots of long lines at food banks. Periodic interviews with exhausted doctors and nurses on the front lines. 

BUT. This has been going on for 9 months. People are tired. People are so very tired. Yet we are entering a new phase.

From the global perspective to tiny Marshall County (46,000 people in rural Northern Indiana) were I helped my community survive and rebuild after a 500-year flood. The outpouring of volunteers, donations, community pride and action was beautiful. Inspiring. A damn honor to help.

No matter how intense it got, one knew that the donations would flood in RIGHT AWAY because the disaster was round-the-clock news. People were glued. People gave. But there was always an understood 'end date' when things would return to 'normal' or at least a 'new normal'

After Haiti quake, after Katrina, there was an initial 2-3 weeks of hyper intense emergency disaster work. Providing immediate crisis aid to hardest hit areas. Followed by mid and long-term recovery work that reaches into years. Repairing homes, addressing mental health.

🧵Most of my career, I've done disaster response and crisis communications. On a global level with @CWS_global (tsunamis, earthquakes, refugee resettlement) and now on a hyper-local level with @MCCF_IN.

Nothing has prepared me for the past 9 months.
